liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Stephen Dziedzic Australian Foreign Minister Penny Wong says it is too early for the federal government to say if any Australians in Israel or the Palestinian territories have been caught up in the violence. “I am not in a position to provide you as yet with that information," she said. "We are continuing to work to confirm the welfare of Australians who are in either Israel or the occupied Palestinian territories. “We are obviously concerned about the situation, and we will continue to do the work to assess the circumstances of those Australians.” While some countries have flagged charter flights to evacuate their citizens in Israel, Senator Wong said the federal government wasn’t contemplating that – at least not at this stage. “I have again asked my Department to update on that,” she said. "I understand the airport still open, that there are still commercial options available “We will continue to monitor that commercial availability. "But I have asked them to look at what other countries are doing. "As yet I understand most other likeminded countries remain focussed on commercial (flights)” Watch Senator Wong's press conference below.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Wong says government is working to confirm welfare of Australians

children.content: Reporting by
Stephen Dziedzic
Australian Foreign Minister

says it is too early for the federal government to say if any Australians in
Israel

have been caught up in the violence.
“I am not in a position to provide you as yet with that information," she said.
"We are continuing to work to confirm the welfare of Australians who are in either Israel or the occupied Palestinian territories.
“We are obviously concerned about the situation, and we will continue to do the work to assess the circumstances of those Australians.”
While some countries have flagged charter flights to evacuate their citizens in Israel, Senator Wong said the federal government wasn’t contemplating that – at least not at this stage.
“I have again asked my Department to update on that,” she said.
"I understand the airport still open, that there are still commercial options available
“We will continue to monitor that commercial availability.
"But I have asked them to look at what other countries are doing.
"As yet I understand most other likeminded countries remain focussed on commercial (flights)”
Watch Senator Wong's press conference below.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Keren Lewinsohn’s family have been evacuated from Kibbutz, after hiding in a safe room for days. The Israeli-Australian woman says “terrorists were going from house to house” while her sister hid under her bed. The lack of reception meant for 12 hours, Keren lost contact with her sister. “The last 72 hours have been horrendous”, she said. They were evacuated “bit by bit” as it was safe to do so and a bus was organised to take them to a safe location. When leaving the safe room, Keren said her family described bodies everywhere. “It’s some miracle my whole family have survived and have been evacuated”.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Terrorists going from 'house to house' in Israel

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Samah Sabawi, a Palestinian Australian playwright and author has revealed what life is like for those in Gaza, with family members and friends struggling in the face of Israel retaliation. "It's a very dire situation," She told News Channel's Ros Childs. "They are under siege, under Israeli occupation. They're literally in an Israeli cage and Israel is harming them yet again." She felt like the world, including Australia, was treating Palestinian life as totally worthless and people in Gaza were living in fear not knowing when bombardments would happen. "This is the first time Israel is going into a bombardment campaign having already taken the green light from governments like the Australian Government and the United States and other world governments," she said. "They got the green light to go in and commit the war crimes. That can I do whatever they want and I think this is the lowest point in the Australian history where it comes to the Palestinian-Israeli conflict." She also said she was now worried about losing contact with those inside Gaza. "Everything is cut off," she said. "I know the hospitals are struggling, saying they are unable to deal with especially the casualties. The death rate is shooting through the roof. A lot of families have been wiped out in the last 48 hours." Watch the video below as Australians share stories of what their families are experiencing in Israel and Gaza.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Palestinian Australian describes 'dire situation'

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Executive GM of football at Fremantle Peter Bell has been speaking to Trade Radio about Lachie Schultz's request to join Collingwood. He wouldn't be pressed as to what the Dockers would be asking for in return, but did leave the door open for Schultz to stay. Here's what he had to say: "Lachie advised yesterday that for a few different reasons he was interested in ammove to Vivtory and would like to play at Collingwood. We're open to listening to Collingwood, but there's a strong possibility that he'll be playing in 2024 for us. "He hit a contract trigger for an extra year on his contract to the end of 2024. We had been in discussion for a further extension for an extra couple of years. "There was an element of surprise that the request came, but we acknowledge that circumstances can change. "He's a big part of our plans and he's a valued teammate."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Next up in our look at the top draft prospects of 2023 is Colby McKercher, our Tasmanian midfield dynamo. As a pure midfielder, there is no better option in this year's draft. McKercher is a prolific ball winner both inside the contest and as an outside receiver, and has uses it well with his tidy left foot. But where McKercher really stands out is his speed and agility. Combine that with his willingness to take defenders on and find creative solutions on the field and you're looking at a midfielder with real hurt factor. Think of a Errol Gulden or Connor Rozee type, the sort of player that can impact at the stoppage but push forward for a goal or two a game. McKercher is fun to watch, because he'll very rarely take the boring and safe option. There has been some talk that teams might be a little put off by the Tasmania of it all, but McKercher has been at pains all year to stress he is keen to head to the mainland and is determined to be a one-club player wherever he ends up. McKercher is a top-three prospect and there is no way he'll slip out of the top five.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Draft Spotlight — Colby McKercher

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Reporting by Patrick Bell The ACT's chief minister Andrew Barr said he's "apprehensive" about the prospect of a No vote in the referendum, as he voted today at Old Parliament House in Canberra. Mr Barr said while many people remain undecided, he accepts the likelihood of a victory for the Yes campaign is slim. "I'm a little apprehensive and a little sad about what I anticipate might be the result on Saturday," Mr Barr said. " It's not over by any sense but clearly Yes is the underdog at this point ." When the campaign began earlier this year, Mr Barr said he hoped the ACT would record the highest Yes vote of any jurisdiction. Today he said he still thought that would be the case. " I'm still confident that that will be over 50 per cent of the vote, but it may not be the sort of levels of support that we saw for marriage equality." The ACT has had its own Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander elected body since 2008. Mr Barr said it had been "instrumental" in achieving better outcomes for Indigenous people in the ACT. "It's not perfect, not every issue has been solved, and no one is suggesting that the Voice will be able to solve every single issue, but it is an important step forward," he said.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ACT Chief Minister casts ballot, says he's 'apprehensive' of prospect of 'No' vote

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The banking regulator wants to give superannuation members a clearer picture of how their money is being spent and invested, under proposed new plans. APRA wants to publish total fund expenditure and expanded asset allocation data by mid next year. Deputy Chair Margaret Cole says the proposals represent an important step forward in achieving greater transparency in superannuation. "It is APRA's aim to publish as much of the data that we collect as possible, especially where there is a strong public interest in having access to high quality industry data that is comparable across funds," she said. "Under these proposals, members would have a clearer and more detailed picture of how their money is being spent and invested, while trustees would be further compelled to remain closely focused on improving member outcomes." It has invited super trustees and other industry stakeholders to provide feedback on its plans by the end of November.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Super funds to detail spending under APRA proposal

"It is APRA's aim to publish as much of the data that we collect as possible, especially where there is a strong public interest in having access to high quality industry data that is comparable across funds," she said.

It has invited super trustees and other industry stakeholders to provide feedback on its plans by the end of November.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Energy giant Chevron says talks with unions are progressing, despite the threat of fresh strikes next week. The company has asked Australia's industrial tribunal to help resolve a 'small number' of issues blocking a deal with unions at its two natural gas facilities in Western Australia. These include details about how travel and meal expenses are reimbursed and cabin sharing on the offshore platform. Chevron says once it receives clarification from the Fair Work Commission, it will be able to finalise the Enterprise Agreements for employees to vote on. The union has given the company notice about plans for protected industrial action including work stoppages and partial work bans starting on 19 October. "While we don't believe that industrial action is necessary, given we are seeking the assistance of the Fair Work Commission to resolve the small number of outstanding items between the parties, we will continue to take steps to maintain safe and reliable operations in the event of disruption to our facilities," said a Chevron Australia spokesperson.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Chevron says deal with unions possible

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Virgin Australia has reported a statutory net profit after tax of $129 million for the full year, its first profit in 11 years. It compares to a loss of $565.5 million in 2022. Revenue more than doubled to $5 billion, after a strong increase in customer demand for travel, despite cost of living pressure. CEO Jayne Hrdlicka says it is 'an important milestone' for the airline. "By creating a systemically lower cost base and a conservative balance sheet as well as investing heavily in technology and our frontline, we are well positioned for the future," she said. Virgin Australia was purchased in 2020 for $3.5 billion by US private equity firm Bain Capital, after the airline was placed into voluntary administration. "Our balance sheet is now considerably stronger and the cost base of the business has significantly improved from recent years," said Virgin's CFO Race Strauss. Earlier this year Bain Capital confirmed it is looking to relist Virgin Australia on the Australian Securities Exchange at some stage.

title.children: 'His candidacy is an embarrassment': The Kennedy blowing up Camelot
